      "edited_at": "2025-09-17T09:26:06.796Z",
      "content": "<p>One major feature of cgroups is that they are a delegation concept: the top-level cgroups are owned by root, but it can choose to delegate a subgroup or more to some UID, chown() it to it, and then allow it to manage its own subtree there. Whatever manages that can then decide to delegate things further, and so on.</p><p>eBPF on the other hand has always been a privileged concept mostly: attaching a BPF program to a cgroup requires privs. So, \u2026 uh, \u2026 now we have this nice delegation concept, \u2026</p>",
